Hello,

I am using VueJS for my frontend and django as backend. Facebook is one of my provider from which user can login, however issue is facebook don't respond with email if user isn't verified with email.

In that case I want to go back to Vue and ask him for email and then I want to pass that email back to pipeline and resume.

Any idea ? Certainly I have seen [this](https://github.com/python-social-auth/social-examples), but i can not get it(using Vue).

Below is my login Process:

```js
        login(provider) {
            this.$auth.authenticate(provider, { provider: provider })
            .then(response => {
                console.log("Is this facebook: ", provider == "facebook");
                console.log("Making another request using", response.data);

                this.response = response

                // Handle facebook provider if signed in user don't have email
                if(provider == "facebook") {
                    return this.$http.get(`https://graph.facebook.com/v5.0/me?fields=email&access_token=${response.data.token}`)
                    .then((res) => {
                        this.fb_fetched_email = true
                        return res
                    })
                }else {
                    console.log("Sending data: ", response.data);
                    return this.$http.post("http://localhost:8000/api/v1/account/auth/convert-token", response.data)                    
                }
            })
            .then(response => {
                if(this.fb_fetched_email) {
                    if(response.data.email) {
                        this.response.data.email = response.data.email
                        this.$http.post("http://localhost:8000/api/v1/account/auth/convert-token", this.response.data)
                            .then(res => {
                                this.login_success(res)
                            }).catch(err => {
                                console.log("Error");
                            })
                    }else {
                        alert("Your fb dont have email. Please insert email!")
                    }
                }else {
                    this.login_success(response)
                }
            })
            .catch(function(error) {
                alert("Error in login!")
                console.error(error);
                console.log(error.response);
            });
        },
```

Here's full stackoverflow question: [link](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58991950/python-social-auth-partial-pipeline-redict-gives-httpresponseredirect-object-h?noredirect=1#comment104236664_58991950)

This appears closely related to #61, but may be an inverse of it...

This is with `social-auth-core==3.2.0`.

The code in `auth_complete()` starts with 
```python
    def auth_complete(self, *args, **kwargs):
        if 'access_token' in self.data:  # Client-side workflow
            token = self.data.get('access_token')
            response = self.get_json(
                'https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v3/tokeninfo',
                params={'access_token': token}
            )
            self.process_error(response)
            return self.do_auth(token, response=response, *args, **kwargs)
        ...
```
The first thing `do_auth()` does is to invoke `user_data()`, and there we find
```python
    def user_data(self, access_token, *args, **kwargs):
        if 'id_token' not in self.data:
            return super(GooglePlusAuth, self).user_data(access_token, *args,
                                                         **kwargs)
        response = self.get_json(
            'https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v3/tokeninfo',
            params={'id_token': access_token}
        )
        self.process_error(response)
        return response
```
So, if there is an `id_token` in the input, although we prefer the access token, we presume that the token we have is an id_token; and although we already have a response in `kwargs`, we go and try to get another one, passing it the wrong token -- which, of course, generates an error.

We were able to work around this by using this class:
```python
class GoogleOAuth2(GooglePlusAuth):
    """
    A backend for Google OAuth2

    Note inherits GooglePlusAuth, because in python-social-auth
    that is the class that is built to handle both server-side
    and client-side flows; the library's GoogleOAuth2 backend
    only does server-side, so we don't want to use that.
    """
    # Override to not ask for a response if we already have it
    def user_data(self, access_token, *args, **kwargs):
        if 'id_token' not in self.data:
            return super(GooglePlusAuth, self).user_data(access_token, *args,
                                                         **kwargs)
        response = kwargs.get('response')
        if not response:
            response = self.get_json(
                'https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v3/tokeninfo',
                params={'id_token': access_token}
            )
            self.process_error(response)
        return response
```
